[HFMD occurs worldwide, and several different enteroviruses have been associated with outbreaks of HFMD. Since 1997, however, large outbreaks of HFMD caused by human enterovirus 71 have been reported, mostly in children in east and Southeast Asia, and cases of flaccid paralysis have occurred in Cambodia associated with a particular strain of human enterovirus 71. In these outbreaks, most children have typical symptoms of HFMD and recover without complications. However, a small number of children with this disease have developed severe complications requiring prolonged hospitalization or, rarely, death. These cases have been associated with prevalence of a particular strain of human enterovirus 71, a genogroup C4a strain. This strain was 1st identified in Cambodia and more recently detected in Australia.

It would be relevant to establish whether this strain is responsible for the current outbreak of HFMD in Auckland. Exceptionally, cases of poliomyelitis-like flaccid paralysis have been associated with this particular strain. Further information would be welcomed. - Mod.CP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1hiF.]
